Prologue
"Please!" Queen Eirwen begged, "don't send her away! She's still a child!" The Ice King, accompanied by his royal advisor, looked down from his throne at his wife. She had given birth to a girl. At the thought of it, his expression darkened.
The girl resembled her mother very much. She had pale blue eyes and white hair with blue streaks. A girl meant weakness in the eyes of the Ice King. After all, up until this point he had only fathered sons.
"You have two choices: Either you kill the child or you send it into the wilderness. That is its punishment for your failure, Eirwen." He spat out her name as if it were poisonous. He always did this.
Frostfell had not always been a single kingdom. Previously, it consisted of two parts, the North and the South. In the North lay the non-magical kingdom, and in the South a kingdom full of fantastic powers. But the North showed its greed and there was an endless war between the two kingdoms until the South finally offered a ceasefire.
The desperation in the South was so great that the royal family was willing to do anything to end the bloodshed. They offered to send their only princess as queen to the North, where she was to bear a son, the future king. In this case, the North would unite with the South to form a kingdom. The North accepted the proposal and Princess Eirwen married Prince Akull.
"I beg you, my king, do whatever you want with me, lock me up, exile me or kill me, but spare my child," Queen Eirwen pleaded, holding her child in her arms.
The Ice King looked down on his queen with disgust. Perhaps, but only perhaps, he would show her mercy. With the woman he had been married to for 22 years, who had stood by him in his worst times and who had given him his sons.
"Very well. The child can remain in the palace," he said, which the queen acknowledged with a sigh. "But," he added, "you will be executed."
The royal advisor and Queen Eirwen looked at each other in horror. Slowly, she turned her gaze to the floor. "Yes, my king." She bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to take the queen's daughter to one of Eirwen's empty rooms. Then he commanded the guards to take Eirwen to the execution square, where all the city's citizens could watch.
As the guards escorted her to the execution square, a loud uproar broke out among the citizens when they realized that their only beloved queen was about to be executed. Some people wept, others screamed and attacked the guards. Still others wondered why this was happening, but everyone agreed.
“Let her go!”
“Why are they doing this to her?”
As Eirwen approached the wooden stake, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. The executioner. The woman who had just been a queen was to be burned. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the worst thing that could be done to a person in Frostfell.
Eirwen was bound to the wooden stake, and the king declared in a speech how the queen had betrayed them all. The inhabitants of Frostfell refused to believe the king and would not accept his words. Then the executioner set the wooden stake alight, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
"Don't give up, Kari." This was the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Dead silence in the palace
Only a knock could be heard from the room located all the way to the left in the South Wing of the eternally cold palace. The servants who passed by always wondered what was in that room. They were afraid of it. Rumors spread among the maids in the palace. Allegedly, the deceased wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in that room and was waiting to be let out.
Their suspicion could not have been more wrong, thought Ivory as she headed toward the South Wing, while the servants went about their business and whispered to each other. They had no idea what lay behind the door.
The rumors concerned Ivory as well, since Ivory was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knock, knock. "Lady Kari, are you inside?" Ivory whispered in front of the intricately decorated door, adorned with snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Ivory wondered if – unlike last time – actual entry would be granted this time. I still have bruises from last time. Ivory chuckled at the thought. Kari had thrown a book against Ivory's shoulder, but immediately apologized when she realized who she had hit.
A single knock was heard from inside, probably to indicate that she was there. Where else would she be?
"May I enter?" Ivory asked. Previously, Ivory had walked in without asking.
From inside, Ivory heard a knock. That probably meant a "Yes." The cold and the sound made Ivory shiver. It felt strange to hear a sound from a room supposedly empty, although Ivory had been going in there for several years now.
"I'm coming in," Ivory said and slowly opened the door. The sight that greeted Ivory in the room was unusual for normal people, but not unexpected for Ivory. Paper was everywhere. Books were scattered, the desk was broken, and several ice sculptures lay around. There were no windows and little to no light. Moreover, it was colder than the rest of the palace (which said a lot). The room looked as if a snowstorm had swept through it.
The girl was curled up in her bed, wrapped in her blanket, and reading from one of her notebooks. A small lantern illuminated the room.
"Which notebook is that?" Ivory asked and sat down next to Kari on the bed.
